{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493282","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493282"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:03:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:03:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1275"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1275","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1275"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.34,0.47,0.09,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1275"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106365"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1275","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1275"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1275"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88828"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"1499"},{"type":"tags","id":"1614"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4978"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2156"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2561"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10671"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10682"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16192"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33297"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35546"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38280"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39211"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106365","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106365"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-week history of lower back pain. He has developed shooting pain down his right leg. He denies trauma, fever, weight loss, or bowel or bladder incontinence. His medical history includes chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, multiple basal cell carcinomas (excised) and an abdominal aortic aneurysm (monitored annually). He takes salbutamol and tiotropium inhalers as needed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 120/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There is bilaterally reduced power of 4/5 in hip flexion and extension due to pain, while knee and ankle power is normal. His reflexes are 2+ across the lower limbs and plantar reflexes are down-going. He has a positive straight leg test at 45 degrees in his right leg. There is normal sensation across the lower limbs. He is diffusely tender to palpation over the lumbar region. A digital rectal examination was discussed and declined.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Spine X-ray","No further investigation, simple analgesia and physiotherapy","MRI spine","CT spine","CT abdomen"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBack pain is an extremely common presentation to General Practitioners. The most important aspect of this presentation is to take a thorough history to rule out red flags, an examination to ensure there is no serious neurological deficits and arrange appropriate follow up and counselling for the patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis presentation can be best explained by a spinal disc herniation. This is a common condition that causes acute back pain and can cause sciatica pain, as described in the scenario. At this stage, \u003Cstrong\u003Eno further investigation\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated due to the history being reasonably benign with no red flags (BCC\u0027s rarely metastasise and therefore would not be considered a red flag) for cauda equina and an essentially normal neurological examination (2+ reflexes are normal reflexes and sensation is intact). The recovery from disc herniation usually takes around 6-10 weeks. \u003Cstrong\u003ESimple analgesia and physiotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E can be provided to the patient to aid with their symptoms. If the patient was still struggling with pain after this time, or his pain fails to improve over the next couple of weeks it would be appropriate to further investigate his back pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eabdominal CT\u003C/strong\u003E is not required as the likelihood of this being a rupture of his abdominal aortic aneurysm is very unlikely. If this was the case he would be unstable (hypotension, tachycardia) and would be unlikely to have survived the time since the onset of symptoms. Surveillance of abdominal aortic aneurysms is with ultrasound rather than CT scanning.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003EMRI or spine CT\u003C/strong\u003E are not required at this stage. These investigations would be indicated if he reported symptoms of cauda equina, such as incontinence, saddle anaesthesia and had poor anal tone. It\u0027s worth noting that while the patient has a history of basal cell carcinomas, these very rarely metastasise and therefore do not constitute a red flag that would indicate imaging. Even in patients with a history of cancer with metastatic potential, a trial of conservative management is reasonable without other red flags present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Espine X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E may be useful in the identification of vertebral crush fractures, spondylolysis or spondylolisthesis, but again these findings would not indicate a change in the current management, so do not offer benefit in terms of clinical outcome at this point.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EImaging all patients with lower back pain increases health care costs, exposes many to unnecessary radiation and can impede recovery by creating anxiety within the patient about a potentially serious condition as they required imaging. Careful examination, history taking and discussion with the patient for ongoing follow up of their back pain can help to reduce unnecessary investigations.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Not all presentations of back pain require imaging investigation.","Sciatica is commonly caused by a herniated vertebral disc.","Red flags for back pain include trauma, fever, weight loss, bowel/bladder incontinence, and history of cancer with metastatic potential."],"references":["Australian Commission on Safety and Quality in Health Care. Low Back Pain Clinical Care Standard. Sydney: ACSQHC; 2022. Available from: https://www.safetyandquality.gov.au/sites/default/files/2022-08/low_back_pain_clinical_care_standard.pdf","Bratton RL. Assessment and management of acute low back pain. Am Fam Physician. 1999 Nov 15;60(8):2299-308. PMID: 10593321.","Park, D, 2021. Herniated Disc in the Lower back pain. OrthoInfo. Access at: https://orthoinfo.aaos.org/en/diseases--conditions/herniated-disk-in-the-lower-back/.","Murtagh J, Kenna C. Back pain and spinal manipulation. A practical guide, 2nd edn. Oxford: Butterworth-Heinemann Medical, 1997. Bogduk N, McGuirk B. Medical management of acute and chronic low back pain. An evidence based approach. Amsterdam: Elsevier, 2002."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88828"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1275"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88828","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88828"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-19T08:47:38+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-19T08:47:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1275"}},"content":{"da